The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       The City Diary
                Samir Das, 25, was arrested in Howrah on Tuesday night in connection with the murder of local goons Swapan Bar and Swapan Das, also known as Chal Swapan and Machh Swapan. Police said Samir was part of the armed gang that shot dead the goons in the middle of Kalibabur Bazar on the morning of August 19. Samir had been absconding since then. He was produced in court on Wednesday and remanded in police custody for three days.     A complaint has been lodged with Hare Street police station in connection with the clash between two unions on the first floor of Writers Buildings on October 27. No one has been arrested, home secretary Ashok Mohan Chakrabarti said on Wednesday. Assistant commissioner Ashok Banerjee, responsible for maintaining law and order in the state secretariat, has been transferred. A government official said Banerjee was transferred because he underwent a cardiac surgery recently.     Bijoli cinema in Bhowanipore faced a bomb scare on Wednesday evening after an unidentified caller told a staff member that a bomb had been planted inside the hall. The owner called police. To prevent panic, viewers were asked to leave the hall, citing problems with the films roll. The anti-sabotage check team and bomb disposal squad scanned the hall but didnt find any explosives. The viewers were later asked to return to their seats.     A 23-year-old security guard, Bikash, hanged himself inside his office in Salt Lake early on Wednesday. He left a suicide note saying he was killing himself because of a failed affair, police said. Bikash was a resident of Sandeshkhali and had been working at the Institute of Town Planners of India for eight months, police said.     Mohammad Sheik, 12, was killed on the railway tracks near Shyamnagar in north Calcutta after being hit by a local train on Wednesday afternoon. He was trying to cross the tracks when the train hit him.                                                                                                                                                                 
